INTRODUCTION

Spiney Lobster (Panulirus interruptus) are a species of special interest in California because they are a key predator in giant kelp forests. Kelp forests provide an abundance of food and coastline protection to shoreline communities. In 2012, two marine protected areas (MPAs) were established in Santa Barbara County at Naples and Isla Vista. The Santa Barbara Coastal Long Term Ecological Research Team (SBC LTER) began collecting samples at five different kelp forest research sites. Two of these sites are within MPAs (Naples and Isla Vista) and three are outside of the MPA zones (Arroyo Quemodo, Mohawk, and Carpinteria). In this report, we explore data from the SBC LTR team to analyze changes in lobster population trends, abundance, and size at MPA sites versus non-MPA sites in 2012 and 2018.

Figure 1. California spiny lobster (Panulirus interruptus). Credit: Golden State Images.

Figure 2. Spacial Coverage of the five data sites. Credit: Santa Barbara Coastal LTER, Danial C. Reed

DATA AND METHODS

The dataset includes abundance (count) and carapace size (mm) data of spiney lobster in the 5 designated sites in Santa Barbara County between 2012 and 2018. The data is collected annually by divers from October to March before the start of the lobster season. During that time, data is collected every 2-4 weeks. Our methods for observing and analyzing the data include visually exploring the data and conducting the following statistical tests: two-sided T-tests, mean, standard deviationD, sample size, confidence intervals, p-value, and effect size. Specifically, we used these tests to infer distributions and differences across these key variables: size, count, years and sites.

RESULTS A: Abundance of lobsters per site

Figure 3. Abundance of spiny lobsters at 5 different SBC LTER sites between the years 2012 and 2018. Counts for lobster abundance increased for Isla Vista and Naples (both MPA sites), while Arroyo Quemado, Carpinteria, and Mohawk (non-MPA sites) have varying declines of count. Data: Reed D. 2019.

RESULTS B: Lobster size distribution shifts in 2012 & 2018

Figure 4. Lobster carapace size (mm) distribution shifts between 2012 and 2018 increased significantly for both the MPA sites (IVEE and NAPL). There are significantly more observations collected for each site in 2018 than 2012, specifically at Carpinteria, Isla Vista and Naples.
